Introduction



A facility that uses or stores more than a threshold quantity of a regulated substance is required to submit a Risk Management Program (RMP) to the United States Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA).  An RMP comprises several elements, including an evaluation of potential accident scenarios and a comprehensive program to prevent accidental releases of regulated chemicals. 



The RMP summarizes the management, administrative, procedural, and technological controls that the facility uses in combination to minimize the risk of hazardous chemical releases to the surrounding community.  The RMP includes the following information:



- Introduction;

- Facility identification, regulated substances, and covered processes;

- Policies to protect health, environment, and safety;

- Hazard Assessment;

- Prevention Program;

- Five-Year Accident History;

- Emergency Response Plan; and

- Planned Changes to improve safety



Kinder Morgan Liquids Terminals (KMLT) submitted an update of the RMP for KMLT's Argo Illinois Terminal on June 26, 2006 for removal of Tank C-11 from cyclohexylamine storage service at the Argo Terminal.  On November 4, 2009, KMLT submitted an update of the RMP for addition of Tank W-1 for ethylenediamine storage service at the Argo Terminal. The 2012 update is for the removal of ethylenediamine storage service at the Argo Terminal, effective December 2011. The 2015 update includes the addition of the Butane Blending process. In 2019, KMLT completed a resubmission to update the information on file for both processes.



The Argo Terminal stores vinyl acetate, a regulated toxic material under the RMP Program with a threshold quantity of 15,000 pounds, and Butane, a flammable gas under the RMP Program with a threshold quantity of 10,000 pounds.



Kinder Morgan Liquids Terminals, LLC (KMLT) - Argo Terminal is a bulk petroleum storage and distribution facility that includes butane blending and vinyl acetate monomer handling operations.
